WEBVTT

00:01.334 --> 00:03.109
Hey. I couldn't find the
article about you teaching

00:03.169 --> 00:05.705
sex ed to seniors, but I did
find this folder labeled

00:05.772 --> 00:08.275
"Senior sex ed thank-you
notes." Don't open that.

00:08.341 --> 00:09.581
There's pictures in there.

00:09.709 --> 00:10.949
Ho! There are pictures.

00:11.011 --> 00:12.422
There are lots of pictures.

00:12.479 --> 00:15.653
Why would you not throw these
away or incinerate them?

00:15.715 --> 00:18.059
Because every memory
deserves to be chronicled.

00:18.118 --> 00:19.324
Even the saggy ones.

00:19.386 --> 00:21.923
I am putting together
a scrapbook commemorating

00:21.988 --> 00:23.524
my first year on
the city council.

00:23.590 --> 00:26.969
This year whizzed by so fast. There
was so much more I wanted to do.

00:27.027 --> 00:31.874
But time is the relentless and cruel
enemy of the devoted civil servant.

00:32.098 --> 00:35.341
It's actually one of the
sub-titles of my scrapbook.

00:36.870 --> 00:38.008
Probably would've
gotten more stuff done

00:38.071 --> 00:40.881
if I hadn't spent so much time
brainstorming scrapbook titles.

00:41.408 --> 00:43.285
Ben and Leslie's day off.
Let's go relax.

00:43.343 --> 00:45.721
I cannot wait
for our day off.

00:45.779 --> 00:48.817
But what if
we took a day on

00:48.882 --> 00:50.691
and stayed here and worked
on some projects? Hmm.

00:50.750 --> 00:52.991
That sounds pretty sexy, right?
No.

00:53.053 --> 00:56.796
Leslie, you've worked non-stop.
Holidays and weekends.

00:56.856 --> 00:58.233
You'rejust
gonna take a day off.

00:58.291 --> 00:59.429
It'll be good for you.

00:59.559 --> 01:00.697
All right. You're cute.

01:00.760 --> 01:01.830
And you're right.
Come on.

01:01.928 --> 01:02.929
Let's relax.
All right.

01:03.596 --> 01:06.805
Hey, April. I'll be gone for
the next 19-and-a-half hours,

01:06.866 --> 01:08.641
so can you water my
plants in my office?

01:08.701 --> 01:10.510
We are all out of water,
actually.

01:10.637 --> 01:12.446
I'll have to use
boiling hot milk.

01:12.505 --> 01:13.848
Are you really gonna do that?
Yes.

01:14.441 --> 01:16.148
Well, everybody.

01:16.910 --> 01:21.984
Wow! It has been an honor and a
pleasure to work with you all.

01:22.048 --> 01:25.325
The time I have spent at Parks and
Rec have been the happiest days

01:25.385 --> 01:27.126
of my life here
in the government.

01:27.720 --> 01:30.098
And I know everyone says it,
but I sincerely hope

01:30.190 --> 01:31.430
that we stay in touch.

01:35.261 --> 01:36.706
What the...is
happening right now?

01:37.864 --> 01:40.105
Today's my last day, Leslie.
I'm retiring.

01:40.300 --> 01:42.405
What? Why didn't
you tell us?

01:42.535 --> 01:44.208
Well, I didn't want
to make a big fuss.

01:44.270 --> 01:47.342
Although, gosh, I'm pretty sure
I mentioned it a few times.

01:47.407 --> 01:49.250
Oh, God, they're gonna
fire people, aren't they?

01:49.309 --> 01:50.947
Yeah, I am two years
from my pension.

01:51.311 --> 01:54.588
Can you believe it? Only six
months left until I retire.

01:56.082 --> 01:57.186
What did Jerry say?

01:57.317 --> 01:58.421
Jerry was here?

01:58.751 --> 02:00.424
Well, this is
my last weep.

02:00.620 --> 02:04.227
Oops! I mean,
"weep." Week.

02:04.324 --> 02:05.325
(LAUGHS)

02:06.192 --> 02:07.262
Geez.

02:07.494 --> 02:08.598
(LAUGHING)

02:09.229 --> 02:11.800
Wait, wait, wait, wait, wait. Just wait.
Everybody wait. Okay.

02:11.865 --> 02:13.401
As much as we
want this to happen,

02:13.533 --> 02:15.069
we can't let
Jerry just disappear.

02:15.135 --> 02:16.876
We have to
commemorate this somehow.

02:16.936 --> 02:21.180
You're right. Jerry, thank
you for your service.

02:21.241 --> 02:22.447
Good-bye.

02:22.509 --> 02:25.922
Thanks, Ron.
That speech means a lot.

02:25.979 --> 02:29.290
Okay, well, I am going to go and
say good-bye to some other folks.

02:30.617 --> 02:32.187
Okay, see you
tomorrow, Jerry.

