have some left in my bedroom.

11:59.485 --> 12:02.159
Oh, well, then, we should
definitely go look for those.

12:02.221 --> 12:03.564
Let's find those.
We need to find those.

12:03.622 --> 12:04.896
Hurry.

12:10.262 --> 12:12.071
Okay, everyone
gather around.

12:12.131 --> 12:13.439
Leslie, I really
appreciate this,

12:13.499 --> 12:15.706
but I did promise Gayle I
would leave by 5:00. (LAUGHS)

12:15.768 --> 12:20.239
She has a tasty surprise waiting
for me, if you know what I mean.

12:20.406 --> 12:21.680
Gross, Jerry.

12:21.741 --> 12:22.879
She made a meatloaf.

12:22.942 --> 12:24.387
LESLIE: Well, this is better
than meatloaf.

12:24.443 --> 12:25.751
When Jerry first
applied for this job,

12:25.811 --> 12:28.690
one of this goals was to have
a building named after him.

12:28.748 --> 12:31.422
Again, that is an absurd request
considering your work record.

12:31.484 --> 12:35.091
But I thought maybe he could
have a room named after him.

12:35.387 --> 12:38.197
So henceforth,
Parks and Rec conference room

12:38.257 --> 12:42.831
will serve as a testament to
your years of public service.

12:43.028 --> 12:44.234
Oh, my God.

12:44.363 --> 12:45.603
Hear, hear.

12:45.664 --> 12:49.737
(SIGHS) "Jerry Gergich Memorial
Conference Room. RIP"?

12:50.236 --> 12:53.513
(LAUGHS) Oh, the guy at the plaque
store thought you had died.

12:53.839 --> 12:55.910
It was a rush job, so we
didn't have time to change it.

12:56.275 --> 12:58.949
It doesn't matter. We can just
pretend it means "retire in peace."

12:59.378 --> 13:00.618
Yeah.
Yeah, okay.

13:00.679 --> 13:01.885
So bring out the cake!

13:01.947 --> 13:05.394
JERRY: Oh! Wow!
Speech, speech, speech.

13:05.518 --> 13:06.656
Well, thank you, guys.

13:06.719 --> 13:09.757
I'm not much of a speechmaker,
but I do like good cake.

13:11.056 --> 13:12.057
DONNA: Uh...
JERRY: Mmm...

13:12.291 --> 13:13.361
You're on fire.

13:13.793 --> 13:15.568
(GASPS) Whoa!

13:15.694 --> 13:16.900
Oh, my God, Jerry!

13:27.306 --> 13:30.617
Well, that went roughly
as well as I thought it would.

13:33.179 --> 13:35.716
I promised Gayle I'd leave at 5:00.
I guess this is it.

13:35.815 --> 13:36.816
(GIGGLES)

13:37.716 --> 13:38.820
Bye.

13:39.585 --> 13:40.893
See you tomorrow, Jeremy.

13:41.787 --> 13:44.666
Well, pretty heroic,
huh, guys?

13:45.024 --> 13:46.059
Hard to make fun of that.

13:46.192 --> 13:47.227
Man, the cake.

13:47.993 --> 13:49.631
Filo Pilo ruined
the cake.

13:49.762 --> 13:51.435
Classic Pilo.

13:51.564 --> 13:53.168
What? How is that
my fault?

13:53.232 --> 13:55.371
Stupid Jerry. Should have
never saved his life.

13:57.369 --> 13:58.575
(KNOCKING)

13:59.738 --> 14:00.773
Well...

14:00.840 --> 14:02.649
Hey, Jerry.
Do you have a second?

14:02.708 --> 14:04.847
Leslie. Well,
this is a lovely surprise.

14:04.910 --> 14:06.014
Come on in. Have
breakfast with the family.

14:06.078 --> 14:09.525
That's okay. I just popped by to
apologize and to give you something.

14:09.615 --> 14:11.253
Is that Leslie Knope?
Yes.

14:11.317 --> 14:12.387
Hi, Gayle.

14:12.518 --> 14:13.622
What a surprise.

14:14.086 --> 14:16.088
I insist you join
us for breakfast.

14:16.555 --> 14:19.764
This guy is the greatest
breakfast chef in the world.

14:19.892 --> 14:22.202
Oh, you know, I'm not
really into breakfast foods.

14:22.628 --> 14:24.505
Really? Your purse is
shaped like a waffle.

14:24.797 --> 14:26.572
Is it?
Please join us.

14:26.632 --> 14:29.169
The Gergiches don't take
no for an answer. Mmm-mmm.

14:29.335 --> 14:30.541
(SIGHS) Okay.

14:30.636 --> 14:32.081
(LAUGHS) Come on in.

14:33.272 --> 14:35.582
Girls, we've got company.

14:39.378 --> 14:41.517
So, you want to
get out of here?

14:42.314 --> 14:44.089
Work just started,
Ms. Meagle.

14:44.350 --> 14:46.660
Yeah, but our work is just beginning.
You know what I'm saying?

14:46.719 --> 14:48.630
Oh, Donna, who's
the new boy toy?

14:48.687 --> 14:50.360
I'm Taylor,
the new intern.

14:50.422 --> 14:52.231
This is the new intern?
Are you kidding me?

14:52.291 --> 14:54.293
Yeah, he went to high school
with my sister, Natalie.

14:54.393 --> 14:56.236
He was a big deal
on the football team.

14:56.629 --> 14:59.667
Oh, meathead jock
type, huh?

14:59.732 --> 15:01.905
Actually, I quit
football senior year

15:02.001 --> 15:03.742
so I could help my pastor
run a homeless shelter.

15:03.836 --> 15:06.840
Oh. (SIGHS) This guy loves the homeless
so much, he should marry them, right?

15:07.273 --> 15:09.412
Anybody would be
lucky to marry him.

15:09.475 --> 15:11.113
Hey, Taylor, do you want
to marry me and April?

15:11.176 --> 15:13.452
Wish I could, man,
but I'm not a "marriage" dude.

15:13.646 --> 15:14.886
I've got a lot
of love to give,

15:14.980 --> 15:16.425
and it just seems unfair
to put boundaries on it.

15:17.249 --> 15:18.421
He gets it.

15:18.684 --> 15:19.856
DONNA: (WHISPERS)
You so get it.

15:23.856 --> 15:24.926
Oh, hey.

15:24.990 --> 15:28.494
Hi. Should I keep
walking towards you?

15:28.627 --> 15:31.938
Yeah, I could stop,
and you could walk.

15:32.531 --> 15:34.636
Or you know what,
we could meet in the middle.

15:35.868 --> 15:37.040
Great plan.

15:39.405 --> 15:40.713
Hello.
Hi.

15:41.774 --> 15:43.014
(sums)

15:48.380 --> 15:49.415
Well...
Okay.

15:55.788 --> 15:58.234
Ron, ask me if I'm sad.

15:59.024 --> 16:00.162
No.

16:00.292 --> 16:01.430
Ron, I'm the new Jerry.

16:02.294 --> 16:04.501
Well, is whining going to
do anything about it?

16:04.630 --> 16:07.338
You don't want to be a whipping boy.
Stand up for yourself.

16:07.433 --> 16:10.812
You don't understand, Ron.
I already was Jerry.

16:11.236 --> 16:14.012
I was a skinny Indian kid in
South Carolina, and it sucked.

16:14.139 --> 16:16.483
It took me 12 years,
but I reinvented myself.

16:16.608 --> 16:18.986
I'm a business owner.
I wear dope suits.

16:19.044 --> 16:21.888
I have fur underwear.
It was all for nothing.

16:21.947 --> 16:23.426
I'm back to
being a Jerry.

16:23.482 --> 16:24.483
(sums)

16:24.583 --> 16:25.687
All right.

16:25.751 --> 16:28.061
I'm gonna go buy some sweatpants
and a Nicholas Sparks novel.

16:28.454 --> 16:29.762
Might as well lean into it.

16:31.156 --> 16:33.568
RON: <i>Tom can take care of himself.
He's a grown man.</i>

16:34.360 --> 16:35.430
Well, half-grown.

16:35.494 --> 16:36.632
He does have a business

16:36.695 --> 16:38.470
where he rents out his clothes
to 12-year-olds.

16:39.298 --> 16:41.938
ALL GERGICHES:
<i>♪ Eggs, bacon, and toast</i>

16:42.401 --> 16:44.779
<i>♪ Eggs, bacon, and toast</i>

16:45.170 --> 16:47.047
<i>♪ Why don't you start your day</i>

16:47.106 --> 16:50.485
<i>a“ The Gergich way with eggs,
bacon, and...</i>

16:54.313 --> 16:56.293
Oh. Me? Toast...

16:56.415 --> 16:58.759
<i>♪ Eggs, bacon, and toast</i>

16:59.351 --> 17:01.729
<i>♪ Eggs, bacon, and toast</i>

17:01.787 --> 17:03.562
<i>♪ Why don't you start your day</i>

17:03.622 --> 17:05.499
<i>♪ The Gergich way with</i>

17:05.557 --> 17:06.592
<i>♪ Eggs, bacon, and...</i>

17:06.692 --> 17:07.693
<i>♪ Toast ♪</i>

17:07.792 --> 17:09.136
(ALL CHEERING)

17:10.329 --> 17:11.433
Very good.

17:11.497 --> 17:12.669
We sing that
every morning.

17:12.731 --> 17:16.109
But it's an extra treat because
you're here to sing it with us.

17:16.167 --> 17:17.442
JERRY: Mmm-hmm.
Thanks, guys.

17:17.502 --> 17:19.710
Jerry, I wanted your last
day at work to be special,

17:19.771 --> 17:21.217
and I feel like
I let you down.

17:21.272 --> 17:26.244
So I made you this scrapbook
with nearly four amazing pages

17:26.310 --> 17:28.985
jam-packed with memories of
your time in the government.

17:29.048 --> 17:31.858
Oh, my God... Well, look.

17:31.984 --> 17:33.793
Oh, honey.

17:33.852 --> 17:37.095
You look great in
every one of these.

17:37.156 --> 17:42.265
You are still the most handsome
man in the world to me.

17:42.394 --> 17:44.499
Ugh! Mom, come on.

17:44.763 --> 17:46.299
Yeah, geez, Mom.
We're eating.

17:46.365 --> 17:48.709
You know,
it doesn't make any sense.

17:48.767 --> 17:49.768
(ALL LAUGHING)

17:49.868 --> 17:52.815
Leslie, that is
really sweet of you,

17:52.871 --> 17:55.078
but you don't have
to worry about me.

17:55.140 --> 17:57.746
I'm great. Here. I want
to show you something.

17:57.943 --> 17:59.081
Okay.

17:59.778 --> 18:00.779
Whoa!

18:01.246 --> 18:03.283
You also dropped that,
clumsy.

18:06.785 --> 18:07.991
Where am I?

18:09.054 --> 18:12.866
I know I didn't achieve all my work
goals, but, Leslie, I don't care

18:13.092 --> 18:15.936
because for me, the best part about
working in the Parks Department

18:15.994 --> 18:19.874
was that I got to be home every
night with my family at 5:00.

18:20.299 --> 18:22.108
And to me,
that's what mattered most.

18:23.969 --> 18:25.471
Little Sebastian...
Wow!

18:25.704 --> 18:28.548
Jerry, thank you for
sharing this with me.

18:29.074 --> 18:30.382
I...

18:31.743 --> 18:33.086
You have a wonderful life.

18:33.178 --> 18:34.179
Mmm-hmm.

18:34.580 --> 18:35.581
Oh!

18:35.848 --> 18:36.849
Group hug.

18:37.416 --> 18:40.260
Oh, here they are. The hug
machine is here. (ALL LAUGH)

18:41.553 --> 18:46.161
Vroom, vroom, vroom. The hug machine...
It's firing on all cylinders.

18:48.927 --> 18:51.669
Okay, I think we should be
adults and talk about this.

18:52.064 --> 18:53.304
I would love to.

18:53.365 --> 18:55.242
I was nervous
after yesterday

18:55.300 --> 18:57.302
because I was thinking
what does this mean for us?

18:57.369 --> 18:59.406
Not as parents,
but as Chris and Ann?

18:59.471 --> 19:02.213
I don't think on-again, off-again
is a great parental model.

19:02.274 --> 19:04.015
Well, I completely agree.

19:04.109 --> 19:06.589
But if there is
a hypothetical chance

19:06.645 --> 19:09.751
that we could provide
a home with two parents

19:09.815 --> 19:11.522
who are hypothetically
together, then that

19:11.583 --> 19:13.460
could be even better.
Hypothetically.

19:13.719 --> 19:17.565
Of course. We should discuss and
consider all the possibilities.

19:18.357 --> 19:20.837
The most important thing
for me and I think for you

19:21.360 --> 19:22.634
is that we have a child.

19:22.728 --> 19:25.106
And I don't want to do
anything to jeopardize that.

19:28.167 --> 19:29.771
Do you want to make out?
I really do.

19:32.271 --> 19:33.614
Hey.

19:33.672 --> 19:36.118
What are you doing here, Jerry?
I thought you were fired.

19:36.175 --> 19:38.121
I wasn't fired.
I retired.

19:38.177 --> 19:39.315
That's what they all say.

19:39.378 --> 19:41.153
I asked Jerry
to come in.

19:41.213 --> 19:44.251
That new intern wasn't working
out, so I got rid of him.

19:44.316 --> 19:47.627
Once again, I object in the
strongest possible terms.

19:48.020 --> 19:49.761
Once again, noted.

19:49.821 --> 19:53.064
I have also asked Jerry to
come in a couple hours a week

19:53.125 --> 19:55.298
until we find
a permanent replacement.

19:55.360 --> 19:56.703
(GROANS) Just when
we were rid of him?

19:56.762 --> 19:57.832
Yeah, I don't know, Ron.

19:57.930 --> 19:59.170
Are you hearing me, son?

19:59.231 --> 20:01.711
Jerry will come in
once a week,

20:01.767 --> 20:03.440
and everyone will get
to watch him eat

20:03.502 --> 20:07.211
and talk to him about anything
he might do or say or fart.

20:08.140 --> 20:10.211
Welcome back, Jerry.
JERRY: Oh, thank you.

20:10.409 --> 20:12.912
It feels good
just to be back...

20:13.145 --> 20:14.419
(ANDY LAUGHS)

20:15.280 --> 20:16.657
ANDY: Classic new guy.

20:17.182 --> 20:19.594
I'm sorry that I spent
your day off with Jerry

20:19.651 --> 20:21.562
instead of relaxing with you.
It's all right.

20:21.620 --> 20:23.759
And after you fell asleep
making Jerry's scrapbook,

20:23.822 --> 20:27.326
I went back to Season 1 of
Fringe to check for plot holes.

20:27.793 --> 20:29.739
As I suspected, airtight.

20:30.596 --> 20:34.169
I'm sorry. This is all my fault.
I love my job.

20:34.466 --> 20:37.037
But in the blink of an eye,
I'm gonna be retiring,

20:37.102 --> 20:39.605
you know, and flying
off on Marine One

20:39.705 --> 20:41.343
with you and
a Secret Service detail.

20:42.307 --> 20:45.550
Achievements are great,
but I want more than that.

20:45.711 --> 20:47.622
I want what Jerry has.

20:49.715 --> 20:51.820
I mean,
we're always gonna work,

20:51.950 --> 20:54.089
but I think we need to
fill this scrapbook too.

20:55.053 --> 20:56.896
Maybe we should
take a real day off

20:57.022 --> 20:58.865
and talk about
starting our family.

21:00.125 --> 21:02.401
Yeah.
That sounds perfect.

21:03.929 --> 21:05.602
Hey, while you
were over at Jerry's,

21:05.664 --> 21:08.235
did you happen to get any information
about his history with Gayle?

21:08.300 --> 21:10.143
Like, was she
a Russian spy

21:10.202 --> 21:12.978
and the KGB forced her
to marry Jerry as a cover?

21:13.038 --> 21:15.075
You know, it's a mystery, Ben.
Let it go.

21:15.140 --> 21:16.881
Yeah, I can't. It keeps
me awake at night.

21:16.942 --> 21:18.683
Hey, maybe Gayle
has one of those

21:18.744 --> 21:21.520
Oliver Sacks brain
disorder thingies?

21:21.580 --> 21:23.890
Like, does she think
Jerry is a friendly hat?

21:23.949 --> 21:25.223
I think you solved it.

